Do Users Understand Light Behaviors of Smart-Speakers?

Increase Efficacy of Smart-Speakersâ€™ Light Behaviors

Have you ever notice the light behaviors on your smart-speakers? Do you know what information those different colors and light patterns convey? Designers have intended to use light expressions to communicate with users, but does it really work? In this project, a survey research was ran with 243 users to answer those qeustions.

Method

Survey

My role

UX Researcher

Helped survey design and data analysis

Timeline

1 semester

Background

Smart-speakers have become increasingly popular in recent years, with the releasing of Amazon Echo and Google Home devices. Designers have used light as a medium of communication in an unobtrusive way. Most smart-speakers do not have screens, so they rely on voice interface and light to interact with users. Do users understand the light behaviors as designers want?

Goals âœ¨ and Questions

Evaluate if the light behaviors convey information successfully

How accurately users can identify and interpret these light behaviors?

Explore design opportunities for the light on smart-speakers

Methods

An online survey with questions about the daily interactions between users and the light on smart-speakers

Recruitment and Process

n = 243, recruited from Amazon Mechanical Turk

Only those with smart-speakers were allowed to take the survey

30% owned two and 20% owned three or more smart-speaker devices

Only 25% said that they â€œAlwaysâ€ or â€œAlmost Alwaysâ€ rely on the light to obtain information

Users correctly identified only 34% of the light behaviors, on average

Insights

Simplify the light behavior system âœ…

Reducing the number of light behaviors will help reduce the burden on the users to learn and memorize different light behaviors that they might not need or use often. It will make the light behaviors easier to understand. Designers can simplify the light behavior system by prioritizing the most common tasks and the most urgent needs of users.

Provide additional context via voice prompts â­ï¸

Using voice prompts to provide additional information accompanying the light behaviors would help. New users can get used to the voice prompt and light behavior and understand what information the smart-speakers want to convey. It helps reduce the memory workload. It also helps users with visual impairments to effectively interact with the device.

Allow for customization ðŸ˜„

Customization would enable users to choose how the device behaves, which will also add less burdens on the designers to choose and develop universally understandable behaviors. It also enables users with different visual impairments to customize for their needs to interact wit the light behaviors. It also provides flexibility and allow users from diverse cultures for their color preferences.

Conclusions

Our survey findings show that the current light behaviors in smart-speakers are difficult for users to interpret. Users from various countries might interact with light behaviors differently. We urge a redesign of the light behavior system to have more consistent and easier to understand light patterns.

Reflections

If I have more time and support, I would conduct interviews to be able to ask follow up questions with users.

I would also segment my users to understand if they have different usages of the light on smart-speakers or different needs. For example, users with different visual abilities may influence their usage; users from different culture background may influence their understanding of the colors.
